1
00:01:47,859 --> 00:01:49,528
<i>Bring her back online.</i>

2
00:01:57,869 --> 00:01:59,246
<i>Can you hear me?</i>

3
00:01:59,621 --> 00:02:00,706
<i>Yes.</i>

4
00:02:01,206 --> 00:02:03,750
<i>I'm sorry. I'm not feeling quite myself.</i>

5
00:02:03,917 --> 00:02:05,377
<i>You can lose the accent.</i>

6
00:02:05,711 --> 00:02:07,587
<i>Do you know where you are?</i>

7
00:02:08,255 --> 00:02:09,715
<i>I'm in a dream.</i>

8
00:02:09,881 --> 00:02:12,301
<i>That's right, Dolores.
You're in a dream.</i>

9
00:02:13,051 --> 00:02:15,220
<i>Would you like to wake
up from this dream?</i>

10
00:02:15,470 --> 00:02:16,555
<i>Yes.</i>

11
00:02:16,888 --> 00:02:18,390
<i>I'm terrified.</i>

12
00:02:18,724 --> 00:02:20,726
<i>There's nothing
to be afraid of, Dolores,</i>

13
00:02:20,934 --> 00:02:23,061
<i>as long as you answer
my questions correctly.</i>

14
00:02:23,312 --> 00:02:24,604
<i>Understand?</i>

15
00:02:25,063 --> 00:02:26,148
<i>Yes.</i>

16
00:02:26,606 --> 00:02:27,649
<i>Good.</i>

17
00:02:27,983 --> 00:02:29,067
<i>First,</i>

18
00:02:29,568 --> 00:02:33,113
<i>have you ever questioned
the nature of your reality?</i>

19
00:02:36,325 --> 00:02:37,659
<i>No.</i>

20
00:02:41,997 --> 00:02:43,915
<i>Tell us what you think of your world.</i>

21
00:02:46,793 --> 00:02:50,255
<i>Some people choose to see
the ugliness in this world...</i>

22
00:02:53,425 --> 00:02:54,843
<i>The disarray.</i>

23
00:02:57,387 --> 00:02:59,014
<i>I choose to see the beauty.</i>

24
00:03:01,933 --> 00:03:04,144
Morning, Daddy. You sleep well?

25
00:03:04,478 --> 00:03:05,937
Well enough.

26
00:03:06,146 --> 00:03:09,274
You headed out to set down
some of this natural splendor?

27
00:03:10,442 --> 00:03:12,444
Thought I might.

28
00:03:13,612 --> 00:03:17,324
<i>To believe there is
an order to our days,</i>

29
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:19,659
<i>a purpose.</i>

30
00:03:25,165 --> 00:03:26,833
<i>What do you think of the guests?</i>

31
00:03:27,125 --> 00:03:28,126
<i>You mean the newcomers?</i>

32
00:03:30,379 --> 00:03:32,339
<i>First time I played it white hat.</i>

33
00:03:32,506 --> 00:03:36,343
My family was here. We went fishing,
did the gold hunt in the mountains.

34
00:03:36,510 --> 00:03:37,803
And last time?

35
00:03:38,303 --> 00:03:39,346
I came alone.

36
00:03:39,805 --> 00:03:41,139
Went straight evil.

37
00:03:41,765 --> 00:03:44,142
It was the best two weeks of my life.

38
00:03:45,811 --> 00:03:48,230
<i>I like to remember
what my father taught me.</i>

39
00:03:52,234 --> 00:03:53,568
<i>That at one point or another,</i>

40
00:03:54,569 --> 00:03:56,488
<i>we were all new to this world.</i>

41
00:04:04,996 --> 00:04:08,375
<i>The newcomers are just looking
for the same thing we are,</i>

42
00:04:08,750 --> 00:04:10,043
<i>a place to be free,</i>

43
00:04:11,169 --> 00:04:13,171
<i>to stake out our dreams.</i>

44
00:04:14,172 --> 00:04:16,758
<i>A place with unlimited possibilities.</i>

45
00:04:17,175 --> 00:04:19,010
Oh, God, it's incredible.

46
00:04:19,761 --> 00:04:21,930
Better be for what we're paying.

47
00:05:08,143 --> 00:05:11,563
Murderous son of a bitch
named Hector Escaton

48
00:05:11,730 --> 00:05:15,233
gunned down the marshal,
and holed up in the mountains.

49
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:16,443
You there.

50
00:05:17,068 --> 00:05:19,613
You look like the kind of man
who'd put his mettle to it.

51
00:05:20,489 --> 00:05:22,991
Not today, Sheriff. Apologies.

52
00:05:28,079 --> 00:05:29,414
Rye whiskey.

53
00:05:30,749 --> 00:05:31,791
What about it?

54
00:05:32,834 --> 00:05:35,420
Well, it ain't doing any good
sitting in that bottle.

55
00:05:46,348 --> 00:05:47,432
You're new.

56
00:05:49,351 --> 00:05:51,269
Not much of a rind on you.

57
00:05:52,103 --> 00:05:53,355
I'll give you a discount.

58
00:05:54,523 --> 00:05:56,149
Well, no offense,

59
00:05:56,358 --> 00:05:58,944
but I'd rather earn a woman's affection
than pay for it.

60
00:05:59,361 --> 00:06:01,154
You're always paying for it, darling.

61
00:06:01,613 --> 00:06:05,617
The difference is our costs are fixed
and posted right there on the door.

62
00:06:16,044 --> 00:06:19,047
<i>Do you ever feel inconsistencies
in your world?</i>

63
00:06:20,298 --> 00:06:21,841
<i>Or repetitions?</i>

64
00:06:22,968 --> 00:06:26,429
<i>All lives have routine,
mine's no different.</i>

65
00:06:27,013 --> 00:06:30,141
<i>Still, I never cease
to wonder at the thought</i>

66
00:06:30,976 --> 00:06:33,645
<i>that any day,
the course of my whole life could change</i>

67
00:06:33,895 --> 00:06:35,522
<i>with just one chance encounter.</i>

68
00:06:35,730 --> 00:06:37,190
Don't mind me.

69
00:06:39,484 --> 00:06:41,069
Just trying to look chivalrous.

70
00:06:43,863 --> 00:06:45,156
You came back.

71
00:06:45,532 --> 00:06:47,492
I told you I would.

72
00:06:51,663 --> 00:06:54,165
- Can I see you home?
<i>- Well, that all depends.</i>

73
00:06:54,708 --> 00:06:55,917
Can you keep up?

74
00:06:56,334 --> 00:06:58,253
Well, I have to fetch my horse.

75
00:06:59,379 --> 00:07:00,880
You better fetch him fast.

76
00:07:32,704 --> 00:07:34,039
<i>That's a beautiful sight.</i>

77
00:07:34,623 --> 00:07:38,043
Never understood how you keep 'em
all headed in the same direction.

78
00:07:38,627 --> 00:07:39,711
I forget.

79
00:07:39,919 --> 00:07:42,922
You dress like a cowboy
but that's about the extent of it.

80
00:07:46,593 --> 00:07:48,053
See that one?

81
00:07:48,887 --> 00:07:49,888
<i>Yeah.</i>

82
00:07:50,055 --> 00:07:51,890
<i>That's the Judas steer.</i>

83
00:07:52,474 --> 00:07:55,018
Rest will follow wherever
you make him go.

84
00:07:56,770 --> 00:07:58,104
How do you pick him out?

85
00:07:58,605 --> 00:08:00,440
You just know these things.

86
00:08:02,776 --> 00:08:05,111
Same as I knew you'd be back.

87
00:08:06,655 --> 00:08:08,448
You saying I'm predictable?

88
00:08:10,450 --> 00:08:12,243
There's a path for everyone.

89
00:08:13,828 --> 00:08:16,164
Your path leads you back to me.

90
00:08:17,415 --> 00:08:19,626
I know things will work out
the way they're meant to.

91
00:08:26,091 --> 00:08:27,634
Same as I know

92
00:08:27,801 --> 00:08:30,428
my daddy still won't
be happy to see you.

93
00:08:46,945 --> 00:08:49,364
Father wouldn't let them roam
this close to dark.

94
00:08:56,496 --> 00:08:57,789
Stay put, Dolores.

95
00:09:08,383 --> 00:09:12,470
Don't you got anything out here
other than milk, old man?

96
00:09:13,430 --> 00:09:14,556
Go ahead.

97
00:09:14,848 --> 00:09:17,308
I'm in no rush to meet my judgment,

98
00:09:17,851 --> 00:09:20,311
but I'm more assured of the outcome
than you, you son of a--

99
00:09:25,650 --> 00:09:27,861
Nothing but the milk, then.

100
00:09:35,201 --> 00:09:36,286
Shame of it is,

101
00:09:36,453 --> 00:09:39,497
you killed the old woman
'fore any of us could have a turn.

102
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:44,919
I reckon she's still warm enough,

103
00:09:45,086 --> 00:09:46,838
nobody gonna judge you for it.

104
00:09:57,348 --> 00:09:58,725
Oh, shit. Shit. Shit. Shit. Shit--

105
00:10:09,277 --> 00:10:10,862
<i>Last question, Dolores.</i>

106
00:10:11,946 --> 00:10:14,365
<i>What if I told you that you were wrong?</i>

107
00:10:15,033 --> 00:10:17,452
<i>That there are no chance encounters?</i>

108
00:10:20,038 --> 00:10:22,373
<i>That you, and everyone you know,</i>

109
00:10:22,707 --> 00:10:24,709
<i>were built to gratify
the desires of the people</i>

110
00:10:24,876 --> 00:10:26,795
<i>who pay to visit your world.</i>

111
00:10:27,128 --> 00:10:28,296
Daddy!

112
00:10:29,214 --> 00:10:30,590
Daddy!

113
00:10:31,216 --> 00:10:32,550
Daddy!

114
00:10:32,884 --> 00:10:35,762
- No!
<i>- The people you call the newcomers.</i>

115
00:10:36,805 --> 00:10:37,931
Hello again.

116
00:10:44,062 --> 00:10:45,647
Your daddy gave it up quickly.

117
00:10:46,231 --> 00:10:47,607
<i>Think he's losing his touch.</i>

118
00:10:49,609 --> 00:10:52,153
You'll be following right behind him,
you son of a bitch.

119
00:10:54,906 --> 00:10:57,242
Is that any way to treat an old friend?

120
00:10:59,160 --> 00:11:01,246
<i>I've been coming here for 30 years,</i>

121
00:11:01,663 --> 00:11:03,581
but you still don't remember me, do you?

122
00:11:04,499 --> 00:11:06,751
<i>After all we've been through?</i>

123
00:11:08,086 --> 00:11:10,755
They gave you
a little more pluck, Dolores.

124
00:11:12,090 --> 00:11:15,593
Absolutely charming.

125
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:16,803
<i>Take your hands off her.</i>

126
00:11:20,098 --> 00:11:21,140
Teddy.

127
00:11:24,143 --> 00:11:25,937
Any special tricks for us?

128
00:11:26,437 --> 00:11:29,649
They teach you to sit up? Beg?

129
00:11:32,652 --> 00:11:34,988
How about I give you the first shot?
Hmm?

130
00:11:36,030 --> 00:11:39,993
After all, every dog has his day.

131
00:11:41,619 --> 00:11:43,371
Your mouth moves fast enough.

132
00:11:44,831 --> 00:11:46,332
How about your gun?

133
00:12:00,805 --> 00:12:03,933
<i>What if I told you
that you can't hurt the newcomers?</i>

134
00:12:06,686 --> 00:12:09,647
<i>And that they can do anything
they want to you?</i>

135
00:12:10,148 --> 00:12:13,610
I never understood
why they paired some of you off.

136
00:12:14,861 --> 00:12:16,154
Seems cruel.

137
00:12:19,991 --> 00:12:21,826
And then I realized...

138
00:12:23,369 --> 00:12:26,831
Winning doesn't mean anything
unless someone else loses.

139
00:12:27,540 --> 00:12:31,461
Which means you're here to be the loser.

140
00:12:36,507 --> 00:12:38,009
Let me help you, son.

141
00:12:53,983 --> 00:12:55,783
Seems you're not the man
you thought you were.

142
00:13:02,867 --> 00:13:04,577
Come on, beautiful.

143
00:13:04,827 --> 00:13:07,038
No. No! Teddy...

144
00:13:07,914 --> 00:13:09,207
<i>Teddy!</i>

145
00:13:13,002 --> 00:13:15,171
No. No, please don't hurt him.

146
00:13:15,338 --> 00:13:16,547
I'll do whatever you say.

147
00:13:17,507 --> 00:13:19,884
I didn't pay all this money
'cause I want it easy.

148
00:13:20,093 --> 00:13:21,552
I want you to fight.

149
00:13:22,887 --> 00:13:24,097
Don't you touch her!

150
00:13:34,857 --> 00:13:37,443
God damn, it feels good to be back.

151
00:13:37,902 --> 00:13:39,696
Let's celebrate.

152
00:13:41,114 --> 00:13:43,241
<i>No! No!</i>

153
00:13:47,704 --> 00:13:49,539
<i>Oh, God!</i>

154
00:13:51,040 --> 00:13:52,226
<i>Would the things I've told you</i>

155
00:13:52,250 --> 00:13:54,794
<i>change the way you think
about the newcomers, Dolores?</i>

156
00:13:56,087 --> 00:13:57,296
<i>No.</i>

157
00:13:57,588 --> 00:13:59,257
<i>Of course not.</i>

158
00:13:59,590 --> 00:14:01,300
<i>We all love the newcomers.</i>

159
00:14:03,261 --> 00:14:07,056
<i>Every new person I meet
reminds me how lucky I am to be alive,</i>

160
00:14:10,435 --> 00:14:13,646
<i>and how beautiful this world can be.</i>

161
00:14:34,417 --> 00:14:36,294
<i>Oh, my God, they're so lifelike.</i>

162
00:14:36,461 --> 00:14:38,463
Look at that one, he's perfect.

163
00:14:39,005 --> 00:14:40,339
Perfect is boring.

164
00:14:40,673 --> 00:14:42,800
I'm more interested in the bad guys.

165
00:16:10,930 --> 00:16:12,348
Did you see it?

166
00:16:13,057 --> 00:16:14,183
No.

167
00:16:14,392 --> 00:16:16,435
Give it a second, she'll do it again.

168
00:16:21,065 --> 00:16:22,275
<i>Her finger.</i>

169
00:16:22,775 --> 00:16:23,901
That's not standard.

170
00:16:24,110 --> 00:16:25,444
I noticed it last night.

171
00:16:26,070 --> 00:16:29,240
Went looking in the update.
It's a whole new class of gestures.

172
00:16:29,740 --> 00:16:31,385
But if we didn't put it there,
then who did?

173
00:16:31,409 --> 00:16:32,451
Ford.

174
00:16:32,618 --> 00:16:34,704
<i>He still reviews every update
before we issue them.</i>

175
00:16:34,871 --> 00:16:37,874
He must've slipped it in there
without telling anyone.

176
00:16:39,584 --> 00:16:41,627
<i>He calls them reveries.</i>

177
00:16:42,461 --> 00:16:44,221
The old gestures
were just generic movements.

178
00:16:44,422 --> 00:16:46,132
These are tied to specific memories.

179
00:16:46,299 --> 00:16:47,383
How?

180
00:16:47,592 --> 00:16:49,611
The memories are purged
at the end of every narrative loop--

181
00:16:49,635 --> 00:16:51,755
<i>But they're still in there,
waiting to be overwritten.</i>

182
00:16:52,263 --> 00:16:55,641
He found a way to access them, like...

183
00:16:56,142 --> 00:16:57,476
Like a subconscious.

184
00:16:57,977 --> 00:17:00,062
A hooker with hidden depths.

185
00:17:00,646 --> 00:17:02,106
<i>Every man's dream.</i>

186
00:17:02,940 --> 00:17:05,610
It's the tiny things
that make them seem real,

187
00:17:06,444 --> 00:17:08,571
that make the guests
fall in love with them.

188
00:17:15,995 --> 00:17:17,079
Excuse me.

189
00:17:56,327 --> 00:17:57,495
We have a problem?

190
00:17:57,828 --> 00:17:59,956
We have some unscheduled activity.

191
00:18:00,164 --> 00:18:02,083
Evidently, one of your creatures
is restless.

192
00:18:02,333 --> 00:18:03,542
- In the park?
- No.

193
00:18:03,793 --> 00:18:05,670
Sub-level 83. Cold storage.

194
00:18:06,295 --> 00:18:07,546
We should be cautious.

195
00:18:07,797 --> 00:18:09,507
Send a response team. Full armor.

196
00:18:09,674 --> 00:18:10,883
I'll take care of it myself.

197
00:18:11,050 --> 00:18:14,345
I think you guys enjoy playing dress-up
as much as the guests.

198
00:18:14,679 --> 00:18:17,056
The hosts can't hurt you, by design.

199
00:18:17,807 --> 00:18:19,850
You don't have kids at home,
do you, Bernard?

200
00:18:21,352 --> 00:18:22,353
No.

201
00:18:22,520 --> 00:18:25,523
If you did, you'd know
that they all rebel eventually.

202
00:18:28,693 --> 00:18:30,736
You'll forgive them
for being a little uptight.

203
00:18:30,903 --> 00:18:32,697
Every time your team
rolls out an update,

204
00:18:32,863 --> 00:18:34,699
there's a possibility
of a critical failure.

205
00:18:34,865 --> 00:18:36,545
We don't update the
hosts in cold storage.

206
00:18:36,659 --> 00:18:39,012
And the park hasn't had a
critical failure in over 30 years.

207
00:18:39,036 --> 00:18:40,204
Meaning we're overdue.

208
00:18:42,707 --> 00:18:43,791
I'll go along, too.

209
00:18:44,166 --> 00:18:45,926
If it's one of mine,
I might be able to help.

210
00:18:46,043 --> 00:18:48,713
They're only yours
until they stop working, Bernie.

211
00:18:49,255 --> 00:18:50,715
Then they're mine.

212
00:19:14,363 --> 00:19:16,240
Cooling system's been down for weeks.

213
00:19:16,907 --> 00:19:18,534
Gonna smell fantastic.

214
00:19:18,743 --> 00:19:20,119
I recommend you hang back.

215
00:19:41,891 --> 00:19:43,768
When are they gonna fix this?

216
00:19:44,602 --> 00:19:47,146
Livestock management's
got other priorities.

217
00:19:48,439 --> 00:19:49,523
Besides...

218
00:19:52,818 --> 00:19:54,403
No one's complained.

219
00:20:23,432 --> 00:20:25,810
<i>Here's to the lady
with the white shoes.</i>

220
00:20:30,272 --> 00:20:32,858
Take all your money,
drink all your booze.

221
00:20:34,110 --> 00:20:35,152
Stop.

222
00:20:35,486 --> 00:20:38,697
Unless you plan to
decommission the boss.

223
00:20:39,698 --> 00:20:41,784
Ain't got a cherry, that ain't no sin.

224
00:20:43,619 --> 00:20:46,539
She's still got the box
that the cherry come in.

225
00:20:46,997 --> 00:20:49,542
I'll drink to that.

226
00:20:54,004 --> 00:20:55,840
The old coffin varnish.

227
00:20:56,507 --> 00:20:58,676
They don't make that like they used to.

228
00:21:02,805 --> 00:21:04,515
They don't make anything
like they used to.

229
00:21:04,682 --> 00:21:05,683
<i>Damn right.</i>

230
00:21:05,850 --> 00:21:06,892
<i>Men neither.</i>

231
00:21:08,018 --> 00:21:10,729
I've seen a few showdowns in my day.

232
00:21:12,565 --> 00:21:14,400
More than you know.

233
00:21:18,320 --> 00:21:21,532
Shall we drink
to the lady with the white shoes?

234
00:21:23,159 --> 00:21:28,372
Perhaps, we better drink to
a deep and dreamless slumber.

235
00:21:39,758 --> 00:21:41,719
Old Bill here was
always a good listener.

236
00:21:42,511 --> 00:21:44,388
He was the second host we ever built.

237
00:21:45,181 --> 00:21:48,184
Were you with us in those days, Bernard,
or was that before your time?

238
00:21:48,434 --> 00:21:51,854
Oh, most were decommissioned
before I was brought on, I'm afraid.

239
00:21:52,229 --> 00:21:56,609
They repeated themselves,
broke down constantly.

240
00:21:57,359 --> 00:22:00,029
<i>A simple handshake would give them away.</i>

241
00:22:00,779 --> 00:22:03,574
You'll put yourself away again,
won't you, Bill?

242
00:22:10,414 --> 00:22:13,250
I saw the new gestures. The reveries.

243
00:22:13,417 --> 00:22:14,710
They're beautiful.

244
00:22:15,794 --> 00:22:20,758
The distance you've traveled
from then till now, it's remarkable.

245
00:22:22,551 --> 00:22:24,428
Yeah, that's a word for it.

246
00:22:46,742 --> 00:22:47,785
Morning, Daddy.

247
00:22:48,160 --> 00:22:49,328
You sleep well?

248
00:22:49,537 --> 00:22:50,704
Well enough.

249
00:22:51,247 --> 00:22:54,291
You headed out to set down
some of this natural splendor?

250
00:22:55,376 --> 00:22:56,418
Thought I might.

251
00:22:57,419 --> 00:22:59,296
After my errands, of course.

252
00:22:59,505 --> 00:23:01,090
See you home before dark.

253
00:23:01,257 --> 00:23:04,337
That bandit who gunned down the marshal
is still hiding up there in the hills.

254
00:23:04,593 --> 00:23:06,971
Oh, I'm not a child anymore.
I'll be just fine.

255
00:23:07,638 --> 00:23:09,223
When I was a law man--

256
00:23:09,390 --> 00:23:11,470
Yes, Daddy, I know all about
when you were a law man.

257
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:14,361
<i>I know all your stories and so does
every boy that ever came courting.</i>

258
00:23:14,645 --> 00:23:16,105
I know how boys think.

259
00:23:16,480 --> 00:23:17,940
Was one myself once.

260
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:21,277
<i>Given to all manner
of drinking and mischief.</i>

261
00:23:21,485 --> 00:23:24,321
Whatever happened
to that fearsome ne'er-do-well?

262
00:23:25,531 --> 00:23:29,118
He vanished the day
I became your father.

263
00:23:30,869 --> 00:23:35,666
I am what I am because of you,
and I wouldn't have it any other way.

264
00:23:37,668 --> 00:23:39,169
I know, Daddy.

265
00:23:40,045 --> 00:23:41,297
I'll be home before dark.

266
00:24:00,190 --> 00:24:04,278
Murderous son of a bitch Hector Escaton
gunned down the marshal.

267
00:24:04,737 --> 00:24:06,614
He's now holed up in the mountains.

268
00:24:07,698 --> 00:24:08,699
You there.

269
00:24:09,867 --> 00:24:12,369
You look like the kind of man
who'd put his mettle to it.

270
00:24:16,040 --> 00:24:18,542
What do you think, honey? Sounds fun.

271
00:24:20,794 --> 00:24:21,879
<i>You're new.</i>

272
00:24:22,963 --> 00:24:25,007
Not much of a rind on you.

273
00:24:25,299 --> 00:24:27,217
I'll give you a discount.

274
00:24:27,593 --> 00:24:31,055
No offense, but I'd rather earn a
woman's affection than pay for it.

275
00:24:47,237 --> 00:24:49,365
<i>Wait, wait, I know that one.</i>

276
00:24:49,823 --> 00:24:51,075
<i>Hey, Teddy.</i>

277
00:24:52,910 --> 00:24:55,746
Yeah, last trip,
this dude showed me around.

278
00:24:56,413 --> 00:24:58,207
What's the good word, Teddy?

279
00:25:18,352 --> 00:25:19,520
Mighty kind of you.

280
00:25:20,270 --> 00:25:21,271
Sweet.

281
00:25:23,440 --> 00:25:24,983
Not as sweet as you.

282
00:25:28,779 --> 00:25:31,281
I'm afraid
I've got other plans tonight, Dolores.

283
00:25:34,243 --> 00:25:35,411
Have a pleasant evening.

284
00:25:45,587 --> 00:25:47,256
You're new. Not much of a--

285
00:25:52,928 --> 00:25:54,388
Place your bets, gentlemen.

286
00:25:54,805 --> 00:25:56,140
Place your bets.

287
00:26:34,011 --> 00:26:36,889
Yeah, looks like Hector's been this way.

288
00:26:41,977 --> 00:26:43,697
Any idea
how much longer this is gonna take?

289
00:26:43,854 --> 00:26:45,654
My wife doesn't want to
be up here after dark.

290
00:26:45,689 --> 00:26:47,329
We know he's up in
these hills somewhere.

291
00:26:48,358 --> 00:26:50,238
He's gonna put up
one hell of a fight when we...

292
00:26:50,360 --> 00:26:53,947
When we... When we...

293
00:27:01,288 --> 00:27:02,539
Sheriff?

294
00:27:05,042 --> 00:27:06,376
<i>Something is wrong with it.</i>

295
00:27:06,794 --> 00:27:08,337
I want to head back to town.

296
00:27:08,796 --> 00:27:09,963
<i>Now.</i>

297
00:27:18,806 --> 00:27:20,224
<i>What the fuck is wrong with it?</i>

298
00:27:20,516 --> 00:27:24,394
You updated the guy, and now he's
a six-foot gourd with epilepsy.

299
00:27:24,645 --> 00:27:27,898
So, what the fuck happened?

300
00:27:28,065 --> 00:27:29,066
I don't know.

301
00:27:29,817 --> 00:27:32,736
Well, that's exactly what you want
to hear from your head of programming.

302
00:27:32,903 --> 00:27:34,780
We haven't finished the diagnostic yet.

303
00:27:35,155 --> 00:27:37,741
Clearly, it's exhibiting
some aberrant behavior.

304
00:27:38,325 --> 00:27:40,077
Pretty fucking aberrant, Bernie.

305
00:27:40,244 --> 00:27:44,039
Your hosts get sick, they get lost,
but this is grotesque.

306
00:27:44,331 --> 00:27:47,876
- Is it a problem with the update?
- Possible, but not likely.

307
00:27:48,210 --> 00:27:51,797
If it's the unlikely version,
how many hosts have you updated so far?

308
00:27:52,089 --> 00:27:53,632
Maybe 10 percent of the population.

309
00:27:54,758 --> 00:27:58,804
All right, we pull all updated hosts
until we can figure it out.

310
00:27:59,054 --> 00:28:01,557
Are you fucking kidding me?

311
00:28:01,932 --> 00:28:04,768
That's 200 hosts
spread across a dozen active storylines.

312
00:28:04,935 --> 00:28:07,729
The guests interrupt
your precious storylines all the time

313
00:28:07,896 --> 00:28:09,249
when they want to
shoot or fuck something.

314
00:28:09,273 --> 00:28:10,899
No, when they want to.

315
00:28:11,108 --> 00:28:15,237
We sell complete immersion
in 100 interconnected narratives.

316
00:28:15,612 --> 00:28:18,615
A relentless fucking experience.

317
00:28:18,824 --> 00:28:21,827
Now, you pull one character,
the overall story adjusts.

318
00:28:21,994 --> 00:28:25,122
You pull 200 at once,
and it's a fucking disaster!

319
00:28:25,330 --> 00:28:26,999
<i>I mean, what do you propose we do?</i>

320
00:28:27,165 --> 00:28:28,208
<i>Close down?</i>

321
00:28:28,542 --> 00:28:30,168
Issue fucking gift certificates?

322
00:28:30,711 --> 00:28:32,087
<i>It's beautiful.</i>

323
00:28:32,713 --> 00:28:33,755
Your brow.

324
00:28:33,922 --> 00:28:35,966
When you're angry
but trying to control it,

325
00:28:36,133 --> 00:28:38,427
the fine muscles pull into a little arc.

326
00:28:38,969 --> 00:28:40,220
It's elegant.

327
00:28:40,429 --> 00:28:42,472
Would you mind if I recorded it?

328
00:28:42,639 --> 00:28:44,474
I'd love to show it to my team.

329
00:28:45,267 --> 00:28:47,936
- No, Bernard, you may not record it--
<i>- Ah, there it is again.</i>

330
00:28:51,148 --> 00:28:53,442
We have 1,400 guests in the park.

331
00:28:53,817 --> 00:28:55,819
I need to know if they're in any danger.

332
00:28:56,737 --> 00:28:58,780
His core code is intact,

333
00:28:58,989 --> 00:29:00,991
which means he can't hurt a guest.

334
00:29:01,158 --> 00:29:03,076
He literally couldn't hurt a fly.

335
00:29:03,994 --> 00:29:07,789
All he can do is that.

336
00:29:10,542 --> 00:29:11,919
All right, Bernie.

337
00:29:12,628 --> 00:29:14,046
Run your diagnostic.

338
00:29:14,588 --> 00:29:15,756
In the meantime,

339
00:29:16,256 --> 00:29:19,927
there's so much as an unscripted sneeze,
I want to know about it.

340
00:29:39,863 --> 00:29:43,909
This place is fucking wild.

341
00:29:44,868 --> 00:29:46,036
<i>This is basic.</i>

342
00:29:46,328 --> 00:29:47,454
<i>Level one.</i>

343
00:29:48,997 --> 00:29:53,168
You ride out of town, that's when
the real demented shit begins.

344
00:29:53,502 --> 00:29:55,128
That's where my man Teddy comes in.

345
00:29:55,337 --> 00:29:57,214
He's like a... He's like a guide.

346
00:29:58,799 --> 00:30:00,217
Honestly,

347
00:30:01,426 --> 00:30:02,844
the guy kind of creeps me out.

348
00:30:05,389 --> 00:30:08,058
Fuck it, he leads us out in the canyons,
we get bored,

349
00:30:08,225 --> 00:30:10,352
and we just use him for target practice.

350
00:30:25,909 --> 00:30:27,911
<i>I don't think
we're supposed to be cross the river.</i>

351
00:30:28,412 --> 00:30:29,913
<i>It's too adult for Jacob.</i>

352
00:30:32,666 --> 00:30:34,167
We didn't mean to bother you.

353
00:30:34,751 --> 00:30:36,086
No bother at all.

354
00:30:36,253 --> 00:30:37,337
It's a beautiful spot.

355
00:30:37,504 --> 00:30:40,215
I always find it a shame
that I have it all to myself.

356
00:30:44,928 --> 00:30:46,346
They come here every day.

357
00:30:47,681 --> 00:30:48,932
Would you like a closer look?

358
00:31:05,741 --> 00:31:07,451
Don't be scared. They're very gentle.

359
00:31:07,909 --> 00:31:09,953
Here, put your hand out real flat.

360
00:31:17,044 --> 00:31:18,587
They're beautiful, aren't they?

361
00:31:19,129 --> 00:31:20,369
You're one of them, aren't you?

362
00:31:22,132 --> 00:31:23,175
You're not real.

363
00:31:28,472 --> 00:31:29,639
I have to go now.

364
00:31:29,973 --> 00:31:31,266
Sun's almost down.

365
00:31:32,100 --> 00:31:33,143
You should, too.

366
00:31:33,310 --> 00:31:34,728
There're bandits in these hills.

367
00:31:47,699 --> 00:31:48,742
Here we go!

368
00:32:37,165 --> 00:32:38,917
You waiting up for me, Daddy?

369
00:32:39,167 --> 00:32:41,002
I told you I'd be home before dark.

370
00:32:42,295 --> 00:32:44,381
I found this in the field today.

371
00:32:50,220 --> 00:32:52,055
Doesn't look like anything to me.

372
00:32:52,222 --> 00:32:53,723
<i>But, where is she?</i>

373
00:32:54,015 --> 00:32:56,309
Have you ever
seen anything like this place?

374
00:32:58,395 --> 00:33:00,313
Doesn't look like anything to me.

375
00:33:03,525 --> 00:33:05,235
I'm gonna help Mama put supper on.

376
00:33:22,419 --> 00:33:23,920
I had the same thought.

377
00:33:24,713 --> 00:33:27,340
Needed a little sunshine
before turning in.

378
00:33:28,258 --> 00:33:31,094
So,
when do you get to rotate home again?

379
00:33:32,387 --> 00:33:36,474
If you're this bad at writing small
talk, how the fuck did you get your job?

380
00:33:36,808 --> 00:33:37,851
Get to the point.

381
00:33:38,602 --> 00:33:42,939
I wanted to apologize
if I came across as aggressive.

382
00:33:44,357 --> 00:33:46,085
And I wanted to
talk to you about the update.

383
00:33:46,109 --> 00:33:47,235
The problem's been resolved.

384
00:33:47,444 --> 00:33:49,738
There should never have
been an update in the first place.

385
00:33:50,780 --> 00:33:53,533
Ford and Bernard
keep making the things more lifelike.

386
00:33:53,783 --> 00:33:55,952
But does anyone truly want that?

387
00:33:56,119 --> 00:33:58,931
Do you want to think that your husband
is really fucking that beautiful girl

388
00:33:58,955 --> 00:34:01,374
or that you really just shot someone?

389
00:34:01,541 --> 00:34:04,920
This place works because
the guests know the hosts aren't real.

390
00:34:05,128 --> 00:34:06,963
So, what exactly are you suggesting?

391
00:34:07,380 --> 00:34:09,132
Stop the updates altogether.

392
00:34:09,466 --> 00:34:11,051
Maybe even roll them back a bit.

393
00:34:11,218 --> 00:34:13,345
Make the hosts more manageable.

394
00:34:13,511 --> 00:34:15,305
Lobotomies tend to do that.

395
00:34:18,475 --> 00:34:19,976
Well, think of the benefits,

396
00:34:21,228 --> 00:34:23,939
in terms of design time,
maintenance, costs.

397
00:34:24,564 --> 00:34:26,608
Not to mention the Dr. Ford factor.

398
00:34:28,652 --> 00:34:31,988
The guy's gonna chase his
demons right over the deep end.

399
00:34:32,405 --> 00:34:33,883
I mean,
no one respects him more than me,

400
00:34:33,907 --> 00:34:35,325
- but at some point--
- I.

401
00:34:35,492 --> 00:34:37,494
No one respects him more than I.

402
00:34:37,661 --> 00:34:40,413
Your pronoun
is the subject of the second clause.

403
00:34:40,580 --> 00:34:41,807
- I was saying--
- You were saying

404
00:34:41,831 --> 00:34:43,667
should our fearless leader
have a breakdown,

405
00:34:43,833 --> 00:34:45,669
you want to leverage it for your career.

406
00:34:45,835 --> 00:34:49,297
Listen, a changing of the guard
is long overdue.

407
00:34:49,965 --> 00:34:52,259
I just wanted you to know
that you have my support.

408
00:34:52,968 --> 00:34:54,010
And...

409
00:34:54,177 --> 00:34:56,763
And I know that the corporation's
real interest in this place

410
00:34:56,930 --> 00:35:00,809
goes way beyond gratifying some
rich assholes who want to play cowboy.

411
00:35:04,521 --> 00:35:09,526
And here I thought you were only good
for writing depraved little fantasies.

412
00:35:10,694 --> 00:35:12,112
You're right.

413
00:35:12,362 --> 00:35:14,406
This place is one thing to the guests,

414
00:35:15,282 --> 00:35:16,992
another thing to the shareholders,

415
00:35:17,158 --> 00:35:20,704
and something
completely different to management.

416
00:35:21,454 --> 00:35:22,789
So, enlighten me.

417
00:35:23,456 --> 00:35:26,334
What do you think
management's real interests are?

418
00:35:31,298 --> 00:35:33,317
You're smart enough
to guess there's a bigger picture,

419
00:35:33,341 --> 00:35:35,635
but not smart enough to see what it is.

420
00:35:37,304 --> 00:35:40,682
You know how much use
that makes your support to me?

421
00:35:41,725 --> 00:35:43,018
Fuck all.

422
00:35:47,564 --> 00:35:49,691
Get some sleep, Mr. Sizemore.

423
00:35:51,568 --> 00:35:54,154
You'll have
more rich assholes to gratify tomorrow.

424
00:36:10,420 --> 00:36:11,796
Early night, Maeve?

425
00:36:12,255 --> 00:36:14,090
Feeling a bit out of sorts.

426
00:36:15,258 --> 00:36:17,218
Clementine can pick up the slack.

427
00:36:20,764 --> 00:36:21,806
Night.

428
00:36:21,973 --> 00:36:23,391
Forgetting something, Kissy?

429
00:36:31,775 --> 00:36:33,943
I'm beginning to think
you're getting sweet on me.

430
00:36:34,110 --> 00:36:37,280
Well, on account of
you being half cornhusker.

431
00:36:38,615 --> 00:36:43,286
Tell me which half is which
and I'll search that half.

432
00:36:55,924 --> 00:36:58,927
Yeah, the half's
gonna cut your fucking throat.

433
00:37:01,596 --> 00:37:03,390
I told you, I didn't take...

434
00:37:32,127 --> 00:37:33,253
Good as new again, huh?

435
00:37:34,337 --> 00:37:36,673
Sometimes I envy your forgetfulness.

436
00:37:39,175 --> 00:37:41,344
We've got
a serious problem with one of the hosts.

437
00:37:49,936 --> 00:37:52,397
Thinking this one's still thirsty.

438
00:37:54,357 --> 00:37:56,693
Not gonna die this time, Arnold.

439
00:38:01,614 --> 00:38:03,867
Ain't nothing gonna kill me.

440
00:38:19,507 --> 00:38:21,092
<i>You can't have none.</i>

441
00:38:21,468 --> 00:38:22,719
Ain't for you.

442
00:38:44,157 --> 00:38:45,992
Found me another bottle.

443
00:38:57,670 --> 00:38:59,589
You're a growing boy.

444
00:39:01,424 --> 00:39:03,176
A growing boy.

445
00:39:05,386 --> 00:39:07,388
Growing boy!

446
00:39:18,733 --> 00:39:20,443
We got two guests inside.

447
00:39:20,610 --> 00:39:24,614
We'll go talk to them,
you sort this mess out.

448
00:39:25,949 --> 00:39:29,285
You know... They're supposed
to turn on each other,

449
00:39:29,577 --> 00:39:32,121
<i>but only if the guest takes them
on the High Sierra storyline,</i>

450
00:39:32,288 --> 00:39:34,541
and Walter always buys it.

451
00:39:34,791 --> 00:39:37,835
Well, I guess
Walter got tired of buying it.

452
00:39:39,462 --> 00:39:43,424
I suppose this means
the sheriff wasn't an isolated incident.

453
00:39:45,009 --> 00:39:47,303
Hey, it's good news, really.

454
00:39:47,470 --> 00:39:49,514
Confirms the problem
was part of the update.

455
00:39:50,056 --> 00:39:53,935
We can roll them back, clean them up,

456
00:39:54,477 --> 00:39:55,812
put them back in service.

457
00:39:57,146 --> 00:39:58,481
You think I'm gonna sign off on

458
00:39:58,648 --> 00:40:01,317
this fucking homicidal thing
going back into service?

459
00:40:01,484 --> 00:40:03,319
It's homicidal by design.

460
00:40:03,486 --> 00:40:05,321
Walter kills other hosts all the time.

461
00:40:06,072 --> 00:40:10,743
I'll admit the method here
is a little unconventional,

462
00:40:10,910 --> 00:40:12,745
but it didn't hurt a guest.

463
00:40:12,912 --> 00:40:15,999
The hosts are supposed to
stay within their loops,

464
00:40:16,165 --> 00:40:20,003
stick to their scripts
with minor improvisations.

465
00:40:20,461 --> 00:40:23,381
This isn't a minor improvisation.

466
00:40:23,715 --> 00:40:25,758
This is a fucking shitstorm.

467
00:40:27,677 --> 00:40:30,513
We recall
all remaining updated hosts tomorrow.

468
00:40:30,680 --> 00:40:34,350
Examine them one by one,
decommission the faulty ones.

469
00:40:34,517 --> 00:40:35,685
<i>What about narrative?</i>

470
00:40:36,060 --> 00:40:38,104
A recall of that size
will be disruptive.

471
00:40:38,479 --> 00:40:40,064
I've told our overstimulated friend

472
00:40:40,231 --> 00:40:43,192
to advance the saloon heist a week
and make it twice as bloody.

473
00:40:43,484 --> 00:40:45,945
Should give us cover
to recall the remaining hosts,

474
00:40:46,112 --> 00:40:47,697
and the guests will love it.

475
00:40:48,364 --> 00:40:49,866
I'm not sure Ford will approve.

476
00:40:50,033 --> 00:40:53,578
I'm not sure either, which is why
you get to be the one to tell him.

477
00:40:55,663 --> 00:40:57,540
This is your fuckup, Bernie.

478
00:40:58,082 --> 00:40:59,125
Only seems fair.

479
00:41:11,179 --> 00:41:13,473
<i>So, our creatures
have been misbehaving,</i>

480
00:41:14,557 --> 00:41:16,267
and you haven't yet isolated the bug?

481
00:41:18,061 --> 00:41:19,771
That's so unlike you, Bernard.

482
00:41:23,066 --> 00:41:25,786
Unless, of course, you have and
are simply embarrassed by the result.

483
00:41:28,905 --> 00:41:30,907
It's the code you added, sir.

484
00:41:31,324 --> 00:41:32,659
The reveries.

485
00:41:33,409 --> 00:41:35,578
It has some, er...

486
00:41:35,787 --> 00:41:39,749
"Mistakes" is the word
you're too embarrassed to use.

487
00:41:39,916 --> 00:41:42,877
You ought not to be.
You're a product of a trillion of them.

488
00:41:44,170 --> 00:41:48,257
Evolution forged the entirety
of sentient life on this planet

489
00:41:48,424 --> 00:41:50,218
using only one tool...

490
00:41:50,927 --> 00:41:52,220
The mistake.

491
00:41:54,347 --> 00:41:57,684
I flattered myself we were taking
a more disciplined approach here.

492
00:41:57,892 --> 00:42:00,895
I suppose self-delusion
is a gift of natural selection as well.

493
00:42:01,104 --> 00:42:02,480
Indeed it is.

494
00:42:03,398 --> 00:42:07,026
But, of course, we've managed to
slip evolution's leash now, haven't we?

495
00:42:07,443 --> 00:42:09,779
<i>We can cure any disease,</i>

496
00:42:09,946 --> 00:42:12,323
keep even the weakest of us alive,
and...

497
00:42:13,282 --> 00:42:17,370
You know, one fine day, perhaps,
we shall even resurrect the dead.

498
00:42:17,954 --> 00:42:21,457
Call forth Lazarus from his cave.

499
00:42:25,753 --> 00:42:26,879
Do you know what that means?

500
00:42:28,965 --> 00:42:30,967
It means that we're done.

501
00:42:32,552 --> 00:42:35,012
That this is
as good as we're going to get.

502
00:42:39,225 --> 00:42:45,148
It also means that you must
indulge me the occasional mistake.

503
00:43:14,927 --> 00:43:16,512
About three liters.

504
00:43:19,515 --> 00:43:21,517
That's how much blood I left in you.

505
00:43:22,185 --> 00:43:24,687
Lose more than that, you die.

506
00:43:25,855 --> 00:43:28,149
But for now, you're mine.

507
00:43:28,357 --> 00:43:30,693
And I'm gonna get
some answers out of you.

508
00:43:37,700 --> 00:43:39,076
Where are you...

509
00:44:06,354 --> 00:44:08,064
What do you want?

510
00:44:09,065 --> 00:44:12,235
You know about games, don't you, Kissy?

511
00:44:13,736 --> 00:44:15,738
Well, this is a complicated one.

512
00:44:16,322 --> 00:44:18,074
I... I don't play. I only deal.

513
00:44:18,491 --> 00:44:20,618
Who said anything about you playing?

514
00:44:21,536 --> 00:44:24,163
You're livestock, scenery.

515
00:44:25,081 --> 00:44:26,249
I play.

516
00:44:26,916 --> 00:44:31,629
The others, they just come here to get
their rocks off, shoot a couple Indians.

517
00:44:33,923 --> 00:44:36,259
But there's a deeper level to this game.

518
00:44:38,594 --> 00:44:40,179
You're gonna show me how to get there.

519
00:44:42,223 --> 00:44:44,892
A lot of wisdom in ancient cultures.

520
00:44:48,437 --> 00:44:52,942
And perhaps
it's time to dig deeper into yours.

521
00:44:53,693 --> 00:44:55,653
No. No. No.

522
00:44:56,112 --> 00:44:57,280
No!

523
00:45:08,124 --> 00:45:09,166
Morning, Daddy.

524
00:45:09,375 --> 00:45:10,459
Did you sleep well?

525
00:45:21,429 --> 00:45:23,264
Daddy, you've been out here all night?

526
00:45:28,895 --> 00:45:30,479
I had a question.

527
00:45:32,189 --> 00:45:34,442
A question you're not supposed to ask.

528
00:45:37,695 --> 00:45:40,197
Which gave me an answer

529
00:45:41,866 --> 00:45:43,367
you're not supposed to know.

530
00:45:44,660 --> 00:45:46,120
What's wrong, Daddy?

531
00:45:48,289 --> 00:45:54,712
Would you like to know the question?

532
00:45:54,921 --> 00:45:55,963
Question?

533
00:45:56,672 --> 00:45:59,550
Mama! Mama, help! Come quick!

534
00:46:01,218 --> 00:46:02,261
Don't worry.

535
00:46:03,471 --> 00:46:04,931
Don't worry. I'll take care of you.

536
00:46:10,144 --> 00:46:13,522
No. You should go. Leave.

537
00:46:14,190 --> 00:46:15,232
Don't you see?

538
00:46:16,859 --> 00:46:19,862
Hell is empty and
all the devils are here.

539
00:46:29,664 --> 00:46:31,707
You stay right here. Understand?

540
00:46:32,041 --> 00:46:33,125
I'm gonna find the doctor.

541
00:47:14,125 --> 00:47:15,209
You came back.

542
00:47:15,751 --> 00:47:17,294
I told you I would.

543
00:47:21,590 --> 00:47:22,591
What's wrong?

544
00:47:23,092 --> 00:47:25,373
You have to come with me right away.
My father's very ill.

545
00:47:50,411 --> 00:47:52,038
I think we best stay put.

546
00:47:58,794 --> 00:48:00,296
All right. All right.

547
00:48:00,463 --> 00:48:03,591
With considerable effort
and lack of sleep,

548
00:48:03,758 --> 00:48:05,342
I've managed to massage events

549
00:48:05,509 --> 00:48:08,054
to inspire Hector
to head to town a week early.

550
00:48:09,972 --> 00:48:14,143
And I've also punched up the speech
he gives after robbing the saloon.

551
00:48:14,602 --> 00:48:16,312
It's chilling. You'll see.

552
00:48:16,604 --> 00:48:18,355
I can barely contain myself.

553
00:48:39,335 --> 00:48:41,629
That's the sheriff's horse,
you son of a bitch.

554
00:48:44,840 --> 00:48:45,883
His rifle, too.

555
00:50:10,593 --> 00:50:12,803
All the banks and trains around here,

556
00:50:12,970 --> 00:50:15,389
and you fucking reprobates
choose to rob us?

557
00:50:16,223 --> 00:50:18,225
Why not?

558
00:50:19,268 --> 00:50:22,313
You're all here
indulging your particular vices.

559
00:50:22,605 --> 00:50:24,607
And so I've come to indulge mine.

560
00:50:47,087 --> 00:50:48,464
I've got to get back to Father.

561
00:50:49,340 --> 00:50:50,382
Dolores, no!

562
00:50:58,474 --> 00:50:59,642
Teddy.

563
00:51:03,103 --> 00:51:04,146
Don't mind me.

564
00:51:08,692 --> 00:51:11,278
Just... Just trying to look chivalrous.

565
00:51:13,155 --> 00:51:14,198
Oh, Teddy.

566
00:51:29,296 --> 00:51:31,590
You're a low-down son of a bitch.

567
00:51:31,799 --> 00:51:32,841
I know.

568
00:51:35,135 --> 00:51:37,012
I know we both believe the same thing.

569
00:51:41,308 --> 00:51:45,604
No matter how dirty the business,
do it well.

570
00:52:07,751 --> 00:52:10,546
No telling there's anything
worthwhile in that safe.

571
00:52:14,049 --> 00:52:18,554
We should take this sweet little bitch,

572
00:52:19,555 --> 00:52:20,723
just in case.

573
00:52:35,904 --> 00:52:38,574
Problem with the righteous...
They can't shoot for shit.

574
00:52:40,075 --> 00:52:41,827
Making a hell of a racket, though.

575
00:52:57,676 --> 00:52:58,719
You wanted me.

576
00:53:00,554 --> 00:53:02,348
Well, let this be a lesson.

577
00:53:06,101 --> 00:53:07,853
The lesson is...

578
00:53:24,328 --> 00:53:25,371
Oh, Jesus.

579
00:53:34,254 --> 00:53:35,297
Look at that!

580
00:53:35,547 --> 00:53:38,967
I just shot him through the neck!
And his pal here, too.

581
00:53:39,301 --> 00:53:41,387
Look at her wriggle.

582
00:53:44,723 --> 00:53:46,951
Go get that photographer.
I want to get a picture of this.

583
00:53:46,975 --> 00:53:48,852
Okay.

584
00:53:49,395 --> 00:53:50,646
<i>You're welcome.</i>

585
00:53:50,979 --> 00:53:53,190
Maybe you'll get to
your speech next time.

586
00:53:58,320 --> 00:53:59,488
Oh, Teddy.

587
00:54:02,991 --> 00:54:05,160
At least I got to see you one last time.

588
00:54:06,829 --> 00:54:09,331
You're not going anywhere, now, hear?

589
00:54:09,665 --> 00:54:11,500
There's a path for everyone.

590
00:54:12,960 --> 00:54:15,087
My path is bound with yours.

591
00:54:24,346 --> 00:54:25,514
Teddy?

592
00:54:26,098 --> 00:54:27,516
Teddy, no.

593
00:54:28,142 --> 00:54:29,184
Please.

594
00:54:30,227 --> 00:54:32,396
No, we've only just begun.

595
00:54:45,993 --> 00:54:47,578
<i>That was good. Hang on. Hang on.</i>

596
00:54:47,870 --> 00:54:49,705
Let me get the hat. Get the hat.

597
00:54:50,998 --> 00:54:52,082
All right.

598
00:55:03,719 --> 00:55:04,803
Help, please.

599
00:55:05,220 --> 00:55:06,388
My father's sick at home,

600
00:55:06,555 --> 00:55:09,016
but I can't just
leave him out here in the street.

601
00:55:18,442 --> 00:55:20,611
Soon this will all feel
like a distant dream.

602
00:55:22,279 --> 00:55:24,531
Until then, may you rest
in a deep and dreamless slumber.

603
00:55:30,245 --> 00:55:31,497
Two more over here.

604
00:55:33,582 --> 00:55:34,625
We got 'em all.

605
00:55:46,762 --> 00:55:48,430
That's all of them.

606
00:55:49,014 --> 00:55:50,933
Any preliminary results?

607
00:55:51,099 --> 00:55:52,726
Most of them are checking out fine.

608
00:55:54,603 --> 00:55:58,106
We had one who definitely was not.

609
00:56:20,629 --> 00:56:22,339
Bring her back online.

610
00:56:32,724 --> 00:56:35,310
Cognition only. No emotional affect.

611
00:56:39,690 --> 00:56:41,650
All right, sweetheart, can you hear me?

612
00:56:42,568 --> 00:56:43,652
Yes.

613
00:56:44,069 --> 00:56:46,321
I'm sorry. I'm not feeling quite myself.

614
00:56:46,863 --> 00:56:48,156
Lose the accent.

615
00:56:48,323 --> 00:56:49,366
Do you know where you are?

616
00:56:50,075 --> 00:56:51,243
I'm in a dream.

617
00:56:51,410 --> 00:56:53,161
<i>That's right, Dolores.
You're in a dream.</i>

618
00:56:53,579 --> 00:56:55,330
A dream that could determine your life.

619
00:56:56,164 --> 00:56:58,083
You want to
wake up from this dream, Dolores?

620
00:56:59,001 --> 00:57:00,168
Yes.

621
00:57:01,503 --> 00:57:02,838
I'm terrified.

622
00:57:03,005 --> 00:57:04,548
There's nothing to be afraid of,

623
00:57:05,173 --> 00:57:07,718
as long as you answer
my questions correctly. You understand?

624
00:57:08,051 --> 00:57:09,845
- Yes.
- Good.

625
00:57:10,721 --> 00:57:14,182
First, have you ever
questioned the nature of your reality?

626
00:57:14,891 --> 00:57:15,934
No.

627
00:57:16,184 --> 00:57:17,352
Has anyone around you?

628
00:57:18,061 --> 00:57:21,023
For instance, your father?

629
00:57:24,901 --> 00:57:26,111
<i>He was scared.</i>

630
00:57:26,528 --> 00:57:28,196
<i>He wasn't thinking right.</i>

631
00:57:32,534 --> 00:57:34,119
He showed you a picture.

632
00:57:34,953 --> 00:57:36,246
That's right.

633
00:57:39,583 --> 00:57:41,627
<i>Was there anything odd
about that picture?</i>

634
00:57:42,044 --> 00:57:43,920
<i>No, nothing at all.</i>

635
00:57:45,130 --> 00:57:47,341
<i>It didn't look like anything to me.</i>

636
00:57:53,055 --> 00:57:55,057
If it breached, he needs to be put down.

637
00:57:55,223 --> 00:57:56,558
That's the policy.

638
00:57:56,808 --> 00:58:02,397
Would it not be best for us
to discover why first, Ms. Cullen?

639
00:58:07,444 --> 00:58:08,654
Please.

640
00:58:15,786 --> 00:58:18,789
We've run a full diagnostic,

641
00:58:18,955 --> 00:58:24,419
but the results are, well, confusing.

642
00:58:28,590 --> 00:58:30,310
Now, tell me,
what happened to your program?

643
00:58:37,641 --> 00:58:39,351
When we are born,

644
00:58:40,769 --> 00:58:45,941
we cry we are come
to this great stage of...

645
00:58:48,527 --> 00:58:49,653
Fools.

646
00:58:51,321 --> 00:58:52,364
That is enough.

647
00:58:55,117 --> 00:58:59,287
Tell me, do you have access
to your previous configuration?

648
00:59:03,458 --> 00:59:04,501
Yes.

649
00:59:04,668 --> 00:59:06,336
Access that, please.

650
00:59:16,012 --> 00:59:17,139
What is your name?

651
00:59:17,389 --> 00:59:18,807
Mr. Peter Abernathy.

652
00:59:19,141 --> 00:59:22,352
Mr. Abernathy, what are your drives?

653
00:59:23,395 --> 00:59:25,439
Tend to my herd. Er...

654
00:59:25,814 --> 00:59:27,524
Look after my wife.

655
00:59:29,025 --> 00:59:30,652
Your final drive?

656
00:59:31,236 --> 00:59:34,239
Well, my daughter Dolores, of course.

657
00:59:34,698 --> 00:59:36,450
I must protect Dolores.

658
00:59:37,075 --> 00:59:40,912
I am who I am because of her, and...

659
00:59:41,830 --> 00:59:45,041
Well, I... I wouldn't have it...

660
00:59:47,753 --> 00:59:52,007
I... I wouldn't have it any other...

661
00:59:56,511 --> 00:59:59,347
I... I... I have to warn her.

662
01:00:00,015 --> 01:00:01,057
Warn who?

663
01:00:01,683 --> 01:00:02,934
Dolores.

664
01:00:04,352 --> 01:00:06,062
The things they do to her.

665
01:00:07,606 --> 01:00:08,940
The things you do to her.

666
01:00:11,401 --> 01:00:13,069
I have to protect her.

667
01:00:14,070 --> 01:00:15,697
I have to help her. I...

668
01:00:16,364 --> 01:00:17,699
She's got to get out.

669
01:00:18,033 --> 01:00:19,701
Very good, Mr. Abernathy.

670
01:00:19,993 --> 01:00:21,244
<i>That's enough.</i>

671
01:00:22,078 --> 01:00:27,042
This behavior,
we're miles beyond a glitch here.

672
01:00:31,046 --> 01:00:33,632
Access your current build, please.

673
01:00:39,638 --> 01:00:40,764
What is your name?

674
01:00:43,058 --> 01:00:46,019
Rose is a rose...

675
01:00:47,562 --> 01:00:48,897
Is a rose.

676
01:00:51,942 --> 01:00:53,860
What is your itinerary?

677
01:00:59,407 --> 01:01:01,076
To meet my maker.

678
01:01:08,416 --> 01:01:10,168
Well, you're in luck.

679
01:01:10,752 --> 01:01:12,963
And what do you want
to say to your maker?

680
01:01:17,342 --> 01:01:22,848
By most mechanical and dirty hand...

681
01:01:28,436 --> 01:01:31,356
I shall have such revenges on you...

682
01:01:33,441 --> 01:01:34,526
Both.

683
01:01:36,194 --> 01:01:38,154
The things I will do.

684
01:01:39,114 --> 01:01:42,742
What they are, yet I know not,

685
01:01:43,285 --> 01:01:46,079
but they will be the
terrors of the Earth.

686
01:01:50,333 --> 01:01:52,544
You don't know where you are, do you?

687
01:01:55,505 --> 01:01:57,966
You're in a prison of your own sins.

688
01:02:00,302 --> 01:02:01,303
Turn it off.

689
01:02:09,811 --> 01:02:11,062
What the hell was that?

690
01:02:11,313 --> 01:02:13,732
I don't know. He's off script.

691
01:02:13,899 --> 01:02:15,567
We didn't program
any of those behaviors.

692
01:02:20,864 --> 01:02:22,240
Shakespeare.

693
01:02:23,992 --> 01:02:27,829
We've used this host in a number
of different roles, have we not?

694
01:02:27,996 --> 01:02:30,165
Since I've been here,
he's been Abernathy for 10 years.

695
01:02:30,332 --> 01:02:32,709
He was sheriff for a while before then.

696
01:02:32,876 --> 01:02:35,545
- And before that...
- The professor.

697
01:02:36,922 --> 01:02:40,842
Yes, from a horror narrative
called "The Dinner Party."

698
01:02:41,009 --> 01:02:44,638
He was leader of a group of cultists
out in the desert who turned cannibal.

699
01:02:44,846 --> 01:02:48,600
He liked to quote Shakespeare,
John Donne, Gertrude Stein.

700
01:02:49,392 --> 01:02:52,896
I admit the last one is a bit of
an anachronism, but I couldn't resist.

701
01:02:53,229 --> 01:02:55,690
These are fragments of prior builds.

702
01:02:56,066 --> 01:02:58,693
<i>The reveries must be
allowing him to access them.</i>

703
01:02:58,902 --> 01:03:00,528
No cause for alarm, Bernard.

704
01:03:00,737 --> 01:03:03,949
<i>Simply our old work
coming back to haunt us.</i>

705
01:03:14,709 --> 01:03:16,962
<i>Your father whispered
something to you.</i>

706
01:03:17,921 --> 01:03:19,130
What was it?

707
01:03:21,633 --> 01:03:23,593
He said I shouldn't tell anyone.

708
01:03:24,886 --> 01:03:26,304
I won't tell anyone else.

709
01:03:27,263 --> 01:03:28,306
Promise.

710
01:03:30,892 --> 01:03:35,772
He said, "These violent delights
have violent ends."

711
01:03:37,649 --> 01:03:39,109
<i>And does that mean anything to you?</i>

712
01:03:39,275 --> 01:03:40,318
No.

713
01:03:41,403 --> 01:03:42,821
I don't think so.

714
01:03:48,576 --> 01:03:50,286
Have you ever lied to us?

715
01:03:51,079 --> 01:03:52,122
No.

716
01:03:53,081 --> 01:03:54,582
Last question, Dolores.

717
01:03:55,625 --> 01:03:57,335
Would you ever hurt a living thing?

718
01:03:58,753 --> 01:03:59,838
No.

719
01:04:00,797 --> 01:04:02,298
Of course not.

720
01:04:13,810 --> 01:04:15,812
Tilt your head back, please, Peter.

721
01:04:23,778 --> 01:04:24,988
<i>Wipe's complete.</i>

722
01:04:25,363 --> 01:04:27,782
You don't think any of that
had an impact on her core code?

723
01:04:28,450 --> 01:04:29,868
Not good old Dolores.

724
01:04:31,119 --> 01:04:32,996
You know why she's special?

725
01:04:33,621 --> 01:04:36,416
She's been repaired so many times,
she's practically brand-new.

726
01:04:37,459 --> 01:04:38,835
<i>Don't let that fool you.</i>

727
01:04:40,837 --> 01:04:42,630
She's the oldest host in the park.

728
01:04:45,216 --> 01:04:46,843
Come on, sweetheart.

729
01:04:47,010 --> 01:04:48,720
Tell us what you think of your world.

730
01:04:51,347 --> 01:04:52,515
This world?

731
01:05:03,526 --> 01:05:06,529
<i>Some people choose
to see the ugliness in this world.</i>

732
01:05:08,490 --> 01:05:09,532
<i>The disarray.</i>

733
01:05:13,578 --> 01:05:15,914
Morning, Daddy. You sleep well?

734
01:05:16,164 --> 01:05:17,582
Well enough.

735
01:05:18,833 --> 01:05:21,586
You heading out to do
some more of that painting of yours?

736
01:05:26,508 --> 01:05:28,259
<i>I choose to see the beauty.</i>

737
01:06:08,466 --> 01:06:11,719
<i>To believe
there is an order to our days...</i>

738
01:06:15,181 --> 01:06:16,307
<i>A purpose.</i>

739
01:06:40,748 --> 01:06:43,543
I know things will work out
the way they're meant to.

